In mid-1979 a transpacific flight cover surfaced that had been

The Flight
On August 31, 1925, two Navy PN-9s took off from San Pablo Bay;
their destination was Pearl Harbor. Ships had been stationed every 200
miles along the route to provide any needed assistance. One plane,
commanded by Allan P. Snody, soon encountered problems and was forced
down, to be rescued by a nearby ship. The other, the PN-9, No.1, commanded
by John Rodgers continued but lacking the expected favorable winds exhausted
its supply of fuel after 2050 miles of flight.
Rodgers made a successful
landing in heavy seas. Prior to landing he attempted to obtain a report
on his exact location from a nearby ship, the AROOSTOCK. Unfortunately
the bearings given were faulty. Since the plane's radio was powered by
a wind-driven generator mounted on the wing, once the plane reached the
water no correcting message could be sent, although it could still receive.
A search for the plane began,
but due to the inaccurate bearings, the
ships and planes seeking to aid the PN-9
covered the wrong area, although at one

downed plane. After several long days Rodgers and his crew heard on their
radio that the search parties "concur that the plane had sunk and the search
